         <abstract><p>Sets of hymns in Ethiopic manuscript tradition may be referred by various labels (or no labels at all) and has no fixed structure. It can contain any number of malkǝʾ or quasi-malkǝʾ. They could be organized as an <seg xml:id="type1ant">anthology</seg> (contains (1) four or more malkǝʾ/quasi-malkǝʾ (2) representing two or more types of subjects (ie Trinitarian, angelic, Marian, etc), such as <ref type="mss" corresp="BLorient573"></ref>, <ref type="mss" corresp="BLorient574"></ref>, <ref type="mss" corresp="BLorient573"></ref>) or a  <seg xml:id="type2coll">collection</seg> ((1) contains predominantly malkǝʾ/quasi-malkǝʾ and (2) includes 3 or more malkǝʾ selected based on a common theme, e.g. <ref type="mss" corresp="BLadd16216"></ref>, <ref type="mss" corresp="BDLaethe21"></ref>, <ref type="mss" corresp="Unesco0813"></ref>), as specified by Augustine Dickinson in his dissertation (forthcoming).
         </p> </abstract>
